  // ==================== Handbook Articles ====================
  "game:gamemechanicinfo-electricalprogressive-title": "Electricity: ElectricalProgressive Mod",
  "game:gamemechanicinfo-electricalprogressive-text": "<strong>Electricity: ElectricalProgressive Mod</strong><br>The mod adds electrical energy, electrical appliances, devices, weapons, and armor to the game. All this helps to ease (or not) survival in the game world, reduce routine, and diversify the gaming experience.<br><br><strong>Basics</strong><br>The law of conservation of energy states that energy is neither created nor destroyed. Energy only transforms from one form to another or transfers from one body to another. The same applies in the game.<br><br>The main source of mechanical energy is windmills. Using generators, you can convert mechanical energy into electrical energy. To do this, you need to transmit torque from the windmill to the generator shaft using shafts and/or gears. Then the generator will start producing electricity.<br><br>Electrical energy can be transmitted via cables to consumers. Simply place the cable on blocks in the desired direction. On each face of a block, you can place up to 4 cables pointing in different directions. This allows you to route cables in any direction and branch the electrical circuit. The cable must be connected to the iron plate of an electrical device for it to start working. Electrical devices, metal blocks, and through connectors can also conduct current.<br><br>Since the wind doesn't always blow at full strength, the energy generated by generators may not be enough to power all electrical devices. To avoid this, you need to connect your electrical circuit to accumulator(s). They will constantly store electrical energy and release it into the circuit to power devices at any time, even when there is no wind.<br><br>To save energy, some devices need to be disconnected from the circuit when not in use. A manual switch is used for this. Install it on a section of the circuit where you need to quickly cut off power.<br><br>For some devices that still require mechanical energy to operate, you will need a motor. It converts electrical energy into mechanical energy. You need to connect it with a shaft to the device. When turned on, the motor will strive to deliver maximum power to the shaft, so make sure the circuit has enough energy.",

  "game:gamemechanicinfo-electricalprogressive-rotors-title": "Electricity: Motors and Generators",
  "game:gamemechanicinfo-electricalprogressive-rotors-text": "<strong>Electricity: Motors and Generators</strong><br>Motors and generators in the mod allow converting electrical energy into mechanical energy and vice versa. To do this, you need to connect cables to them and connect via a shaft. <br><br><strong>Game Mechanics Features</strong><br>Motors and generators most closely model the behavior of such devices from real life. DC machines were taken as an example. Therefore, to better understand how to use them and in what situations, you need to understand the laws they operate by. <br>All rotating mechanisms in the game, including shafts and gears, have two basic parameters: torque and resistance. Torque characterizes the force with which the mechanism rotates the shaft, and resistance characterizes the friction forces and losses that can occur during operation. The torque of shafts and gears is zero. The game engine sums all torques and calculates the shaft speed and its acceleration/deceleration. If the torque is greater than the resistance, the shaft speed will increase. If vice versa, it will decrease. Moreover, both of these parameters change according to certain laws. Usually, resistance increases with speed.<br><br><strong>Generators</strong><br>In the mod, generators have the following additional parameters: <br><i>I_max</i> – maximum energy generation value; <br><i>speed_max</i> – maximum nominal rotational speed; <br><i>resistance_factor</i> – multiplier for resistance; <br><i>resistance_load</i> – constant component of resistance (achieved at I_max). <br><br>The generator's energy generation depends only on the shaft speed and is calculated proportionally to the shaft speed. When exceeding the <i>speed_max</i> value, the generation equals <i>power = I_max</i>. <br>At the same time, the resistance first increases linearly, and after exceeding <i>speed_max</i>, it increases quadratically. The resistance also depends directly proportionally on the load of the electrical circuit on this generator. Therefore, in the absence of consumption, the generator will create minimal resistance.<br><br><strong>Motors</strong><br>In the mod, motors have the following additional parameters: <br><i>I_min</i> – minimum energy value required for the motor to start operating; <br><i>I_max</i> – maximum energy consumption value; <br><i>torque_max</i> – maximum torque; <br><i>kpd_max</i> – Efficiency;<br><i>speed_max</i> – maximum nominal rotational speed; <br><i>resistance_factor</i> – multiplier for resistance. <br><br>The motor produces torque directly proportionally to the energy available to it. The motor also takes its own efficiency into account.<br><br>The motor's resistance is calculated similarly to the generator, except <i>resistance_load</i> is zero.",

  "game:gamemechanicinfo-electricalprogressive-princip-title": "Electricity: Current Behavior, Voltage",
  "game:gamemechanicinfo-electricalprogressive-princip-text": "<strong>Electricity: Current Behavior, Voltage</strong><br>Electric current now flows through conductors, obeying the laws of physics. Some may need to reopen their physics textbooks!<br><br><strong>New Behavior Features</strong><br>Electric current moves in conductors in the form of energy packets, except in instantaneous mode. Energy packets travel along the shortest path from sources to consumers. Also, cables and devices now have their own electrical conductor parameters: resistivity (depends on the material), cross-sectional area, maximum current (exceeding risks burning out), maximum voltage. The current value is calculated according to Ohm's law for a circuit segment, for all energy packets currently passing through that face/block. The direction of energy movement is also taken into account: if energy moves in opposite directions, the corresponding currents are algebraically subtracted (a consequence of Kirchhoff's first law). To prevent cables from burning out, they can be thickened. To do this, take a cable of the same type as the one already placed in your hand and click on it while holding the Shift key. This increases the current capacity of the circuit. But keep in mind, losses in the conductor are calculated according to the Joule-Lenz law. Increasing the passing current greatly increases energy losses. To transmit energy over long distances, you can increase the voltage or use accumulators as buffer storage.<br><br><strong>Voltages</strong><br>Now, different devices require not only different amounts of energy but also different voltages. Exceeding the voltage for a device/cable risks it burning out. You can increase or decrease voltage using a transformer - it works in both directions. So be careful when connecting wires of different voltages! Higher voltage allows more energy to be transmitted through wires.<br><br><strong>Interaction with the Environment</strong><br>Now, uninsulated cables and metal blocks will damage all entities upon contact. The higher the voltage in the circuit, the more damage they will receive. Burned devices and cables will also deal damage. Insulated cables and all working devices are safe to touch.<br><br>All cables and devices have a moisture resistance parameter. If there is no moisture resistance, your device/cable risks burning out upon contact with rain, snow, hail, or spilled water nearby! Upon contact with lava, they burn, break, and will most likely be destroyed. Be careful.",


  "game:gamemechanicinfo-electricalprogressive-immersive-title": "Electricity: Immersive Wires",
  "game:gamemechanicinfo-electricalprogressive-immersive-text": "<strong>Electricity: Immersive Wires</strong><br>The immersive network is designed to transmit energy over long distances at high voltage (512V). The principle of current flow here is similar to a normal grid: energy flows from generators to consumers, but with significantly higher capacity.<br><br><strong>Safety and Tools</strong><br>Working with immersive wires without an <a href=\"handbooksearch://Electrician Kit\">electrician's kit<\/a> is extremely dangerous and impossible. The tool protects against electric shock and allows you to see network parameters on hover.<br><br><strong>Placement Features</strong><br>Unlike regular cables, immersive wires can only be placed on special insulators. Wires also cannot be routed through walls or blocks — upon contact they shatter and drop. For this purpose, use through-connectors.<br><br><strong>Environmental Durability</strong><br>Immersive wires are not afraid of precipitation: rain or snow will not cause a short circuit or burnout, even if the cable is uninsulated. However, exposed conductors remain dangerous to living beings upon direct contact — they will receive an electric shock.<br><br><strong>Warning: Fire!</strong><br>High voltage and current in uninsulated immersive wires can cause ignition. Contact with flammable blocks may result in fire. Use insulated versions of wires or keep them away from flammable materials.",



